    <article style="padding: 1.5rem;">
      <h1>About the Philosophy</h1>
      
      <p>
        Social media platforms are deliberately designed loops engineered to capture your attention and provide instant dopamine rewards. Breaking free from this loop doesn't require sudden, perfect discipline—it requires better alternatives.
      </p>

      <blockquote>
        <strong>The kettle method:</strong> If you organize a time for social media with a clear, naturally constrained window (like the time it takes for a kettle to boil), it works far better than an open-ended block.
      </blockquote>

      <h3>Key Principles</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Frequency over Perfection:</strong> Missed days shouldn't break your momentum or invite guilt. Continuing the streak is about showing up again, not having a perfect record.</li>
        <li><strong>Opt-in Novelty:</strong> The Dopamine Roulette diversifies your daily activities by introducing random suggestions. If we landing on different types of rewards, our urge to search for novelty elsewhere decreases.</li>
        <li><strong>Compassionate Logging:</strong> When you get distracted or slip, acknowledging it honestly and planning a tiny adjustment for tomorrow is a victory. Shame stops progress; awareness builds it.</li>
      </ul>

      <hr />

      <footer style="margin-top: 1rem; border-top: none; padding: 0;">
        <p style="font-style: italic; margin: 0; color: var(--muted-color);">
          Original concept and design advice by <strong>luismtapiab</strong>.
        </p>
      </footer>
    </article>

